              <table width="98%" height="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" summary="layout table">
                <tr> <!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="title" --> 
                  <td align="left" valign="top" class="maintitle"><strong>Managing 
                    your money and budgeting</strong>&nbsp;<strong></strong></td>
                  <!-- InstanceEndEditable --></tr>
                <tr> 
                  <td align="left" valign="top" class="bodytext">&nbsp; </td>
                </tr>
                <tr> <!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="main text" --> 
                  <td align="left" valign="top" class="bodytext"> <p class="bodytext"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><br>
                      </font><span class="bodytext"><a href="#budget">Why budget?</a><br>
                      <a href="#howtobudget">How to budget</a><br>
                      <a href="#example">Example of a basic student budget</a><br>
                      <a href="#tips">Budgeting tips</a><br>
                      <a href="#difficulties">If you are having difficulties&#8230;&#8230;.                      </a></span></p>
                    <p class="bodytext"><a href="http://www.leedstrinity.ac.uk/moneymatters/budgeting/index.htm">See Money Matters section of the College website for more detailed budgeting advice </a></p>
                    <p class="bodytext"><strong><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><a name="budget"></a></font>Why 
                      budget?</strong><br>
                      As a student it is important to give some thought to your 
                      finances to make sure your limited income goes as far as 
                      possible. When you receive your first loan instalment it 
                      may seem like a small fortune, but remember you have to 
                      make this last until you receive your next instalment in 
                      January. To make sure that you do not run into financial 
                      difficulties you need to plan and stick to a budget. </p>
                    <p class="bodytext"><a href="#top">top</a><br>
                      <br>
                      <strong><a name="howtobudget"></a>How to budget</strong></p>
                    <p>Firstly calculate your guaranteed income over the academic 
                      year, which is on average 39 weeks including the Christmas 
                      and Easter vacations. Include your student loan, any additional 
                      grants, parental contribution and any savings. </p>
                    <p>Next calculate your essential expenditure over the academic 
                      year. You could either use the expenditure figures given 
                      in our example of a basic student budget below, or use your 
                      own figures according to your individual needs and priorities. 
                      Try to be as realistic and accurate as possible. You can 
                      adjust your figures as your situation changes.</p>
                    <p>If you want help with planning your budget, the <a href="mailto:studentfinance@tasc.ac.uk">student 
                      adviser</a> will be happy to assist you.</p>
                    <p class="bodytext"><a href="#top">top</a><br>
                      <br>
                      <br>
                      <strong><a name="example"></a>Example of a basic student 
                      budget</strong> <strong>(2006/07)</strong></p>
                    <table width="100%" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" summary="A table to show an example of a basic student budget">
                      <tr bgcolor="#999966"> 
                        <td width="41%" class="bodytext"><strong>Essential expenditure</strong></td>
                        <td width="30%" class="bodytext"><strong>Weekly amount<br>
                          (private rented)</strong></td>
                        <td width="29%" class="bodytext"><strong>Weekly amount<br>
                          (Halls) </strong></td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr> 
                        <td class="bodytext">Accommodation</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;50</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;75</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr> 
                        <td class="bodytext">Utility bills icluding telephone</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;10</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;5</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr> 
                        <td class="bodytext">TV licence/Household insurance</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;5</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;5</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr> 
                        <td class="bodytext">Travel including travel home</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;12</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;5</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr> 
                        <td class="bodytext">Food &amp; household goods</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;28</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;7</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr> 
                        <td class="bodytext">Clothes &amp; laundry</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;10</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;10</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr> 
                        <td class="bodytext">Essential books </td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;5</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;5</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr> 
                        <td class="bodytext">Other study related costs</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;5</td>
                        <td class="bodytext">&pound;5</td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr bgcolor="#999966"> 
                        <td class="bodytext"><strong>Weekly total </strong></td>
                        <td class="bodytext"><strong>&pound;125</strong></td>
                        <td class="bodytext"><strong>&pound;117</strong></td>
                      </tr>
                    </table>
                    <span class="bodytext"><br>
                    </span> <table width="100%" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" summary="A table to show the total expenditure over the academic year">
                      <tr> 
                        <td width="41%" class="bodytext"><strong>Total expenditure 
                          over academic year excluding vacations (30 weeks)</strong></td>
                        <td width="30%" valign="top" class="bodytext"><strong>&pound;3750</strong></td>
                        <td width="29%" valign="top" class="bodytext"><strong>&pound;3510</strong></td>
                      </tr>
                    </table>
                    <span class="bodytext"><br>
                    </span> <table width="100%" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" summary="A table to show the total income over the academic year">
                      <tr> 
                        <td width="41%" valign="top" class="bodytext"><strong>Total 
                          income over academic year (maximum Student Loan)</strong></td>
                        <td valign="top" class="bodytext"><strong>&pound;4195</strong></td>
                      </tr>
                    </table>
                    <span class="bodytext"><br>
                    </span> <table width="100%" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" summary="A table to show the total income minus total expenditure over the academic year">
                      <tr bgcolor="#999966"> 
                        <td width="41%" valign="top" class="bodytext"><strong>Total 
                          income minus total expenditure = surplus/deficit</strong></td>
                        <td width="30%" valign="top" class="bodytext"><strong>+&pound;445</strong></td>
                        <td width="29%" valign="top" class="bodytext"><strong>+&pound;685</strong></td>
                      </tr>
                    </table>
                    <p class="bodytext"><br>
                      As you can see from the example budget, the maximum student 
                      loan just covers basic expenditure term-time only and doesn&#8217;t 
                      leave much for other expenditure such as social and leisure 
                      costs. If you are an independent student and your loan has 
                      to cover you throughout the holidays as well (39 weeks and 
                      possibly 52 if you cannot work throughout the summer vacation) 
                      then the loan does not even cover your basic living costs. 
                    </p>
                    <p class="bodytext"><a href="#top">top</a><br>
                      <br>
                      <strong><a name="tips"></a>Budgeting tips</strong> </p>
                    <ul>
                      <li> If your parents have been assessed to make a contribution 
                        towards your living costs  (check your LEA Financial 
                        Assessment form to find this out), discuss with your parents 
                        when and how you will receive this contribution e.g. weekly, 
                        monthly or in a lump sum.</li>
                      <li>Student loans are paid in three instalments for full-time 
                        students. Budget carefully for this.</li>
                      <li> Try and stick to your weekly budget. Withdraw the money 
                        you need for the week and try to avoid making small cash 
                        machine withdrawals &#8211; these mount up very quickly!</li>
                      <li>Test your budget. Keep a record of what you spend. After 
                        a week/month you can then check your outgoings and see 
                        how accurate your expenditure predictions have been. </li>
                      <li> Don&#8217;t rush out and buy every book on your course 
                        list. Many may not be essential and you may be able to 
                        get some of them second hand. Log on to <a href="http://www.studentbooks.co.uk">www.studentbooks.co.uk</a></li>
                      <li> If you have to pay for healthcare costs (glasses, prescriptions 
                        etc.) make sure you complete a HC1 form first to see if 
                        you are eligible for any financial assistance from the 
                        NHS. Forms are available from your doctor.</li>
                      <li>If your parents' income drops by 15% or more, you can 
                        apply to have your tuition fee contribution (old system students only) and student 
                        loan entitlement reassessed.</li>
                      <li> Make sure you get all possible student discounts for 
                        travel, shopping and your social life. Look at the National 
                        Union of Students website for further information <a href="http://www.nusonline.co.uk">www.nusonline.co.uk</a></li>
                    </ul>
                    <p class="bodytext"><a href="#top">top</a> </p>
                    <p class="bodytext"><strong><a name="difficulties"></a>If 
                      you are having difficulties&#8230;&#8230;.</strong><br>
                      Please do not ignore any financial difficulties you have 
                      as they may become a major problem if not dealt with early 
                      on. Staff in the Student Suport Centre will be happy to discuss any money problems 
                      you are having and can offer advice on student funding, 
                      budgeting and debt problems</p>
                    <p class="bodytext"><br>
                      <a href="#top">top</a></p>
                    <p class="bodytext">&nbsp;</p>
